 =20
   =20
      Stress tests
   =20
 =20

If you are a risk manager at a big bank, you might want to run some stress =
tests examining how your bank will perform under stressful scenarios. If yo=
u are creative and good at your job, you will have fun thinking up the scen=
arios. You will get in a room with some of your subordinates, and ideally w=
ith some front-line traders and managers, and brainstorm bad stuff that mig=
ht happen.
Your brainstorming might include some history: =E2=80=9CWhat if 2008 happen=
s again?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhat if 1929 happens again?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWh=
at if  LTCM happens again?=E2=80=9D It might include some simple numerical =
questions: =E2=80=9CWhat if the S&P falls by 20%?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhat if=
 the Fed raises rates to 7%?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhat if the Fed lowers rates=
 to 0%?=E2=80=9D You might think about social and geopolitical and technolo=
gical questions and try to translate them into economic scenarios: =E2=80=
=9CWhat if nobody goes back to the office and office rents fall 50%?=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9CWhat if artificial intelligence causes mass unemployment?=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhat if Russia=E2=80=99s war in Ukraine keeps pushing up oi=
l prices?=E2=80=9D You might think about scenarios specific to your bank=E2=
=80=99s operations: =E2=80=9CWhat if our CEO gets run over by a bus?=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9CWhat if our CEO steals the corporate treasury?=E2=80=9D
Have fun, go nuts, be creative. Think of lots of scenarios. Then model how =
those scenarios will translate into market prices, how they will affect you=
r funding costs and the cash flows from your assets. Then model how much ca=
pital and liquidity you will have in each scenario. Part of the goal here i=
s to make sure that you will have plenty of capital and liquidity in a wide=
 range of stressful scenarios. Part of the goal is to figure out which scen=
arios will be worse for you, so you can know what to worry about and hedge:=
 If your model tells you that you=E2=80=99ll be fine if the Fed raises rate=
s and bankrupt if it lowers rates, maybe you should do something about that=
.=C2=A0
If there is some specific event that you are worried about =E2=80=94=C2=A0s=
ome new worry that crops up =E2=80=94 you might sit down and design a stres=
s test for that event to make sure that you=E2=80=99d survive it. But your =
overall approach to stress testing will be something like =E2=80=9Clet=E2=
=80=99s constantly think of new things to worry about, and test for those.=
=E2=80=9D It will not be =E2=80=9Clet me think of the one biggest thing to =
worry about, and test only for that.=E2=80=9D Lots of things can go wrong i=
n different directions! If you only worry about one thing, you will miss th=
e other things.
Also separately the Federal Reserve conducts annual stress tests for big US=
 banks, but those are =E2=80=A6=C2=A0different. The Fed=E2=80=99s stress te=
sts were created after the 2008 crisis, basically to shore up confidence in=
 the banks so that they could raise capital. The Fed is in the business of =
supervising big banks, and as part of that business it prods the banks to c=
onsider various risks, to prepare for different scenarios, to build a robus=
t culture of stress testing and risk management. But the Fed=E2=80=99s offi=
cial stress tests are a public exercise designed to make sure =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0and tell everyone =E2=80=94=C2=A0that the banking system could survive a=
nother 2008.=C2=A0
And so each year the Fed sits down and thinks something like =E2=80=9Cwhat =
is the most plausible way for 2008 to happen this year,=E2=80=9D and then i=
t writes one stress-test scenario
  [1]
 that is basically =E2=80=9Cthere=E2=80=99s a recession and real estate pri=
ces collapse,=E2=80=9D and the banks run their models to see how much money=
 they would lose in that scenario, and generally the answer is =E2=80=9Ca c=
ertain amount, but not enough to leave us undercapitalized,=E2=80=9D and th=
e banks pass the stress tests.=C2=A0
This became  slightly awkward in 2020 when the stress-test scenario involve=
d=C2=A0the US unemployment rate peaking at 10%, while the actual stress of =
Covid-19 caused unemployment to peak at 14.7%. If you ask questions like =
=E2=80=9Ccan banks survive another 2008,=E2=80=9D you will not quite get an=
 answer to the question =E2=80=9Ccan banks survive a global pandemic?=E2=80=
=9D The answer to that question, however, turned out to be yes: For a combi=
nation of reasons (supportive government policy and Fed lending, but also p=
rofiting on volatility), the big banks did pretty well in Covid.
It also became slightly awkward this year when the Fed released its stress-=
test scenario=C2=A0in February, and it went like this:

The severely adverse scenario is characterized by a severe global recession=
 accompanied by a period of heightened stress in both commercial and reside=
ntial real estate markets, as well as in corporate debt markets. The U.S. u=
nemployment rate rises nearly 6=C2=BD percentage points from the starting p=
oint of the scenario in the fourth quarter of 2022 to its peak of 10 percen=
t in the third quarter of 2024. The sharp decline in economic activity is a=
lso accompanied by an increase in market volatility, widening corporate bon=
d spreads, and a collapse in asset prices, including a 38 percent decline i=
n house prices and a 40 percent decline in commercial real estate prices. =
=E2=80=A6
The rising unemployment rate and the rapid decline in aggregate demand for =
goods and services significantly reduce inflationary pressures. =E2=80=A6
Short-term interest rates, as measured by the 3-month Treasury rate, fall s=
ignificantly to near zero by the third quarter of 2023 and remain there for=
 the remainder of the scenario. Long-term interest rates, as measured by th=
e 10-year Treasury yield, fall by nearly 3=C2=BC percentage points by the s=
econd quarter of 2023, and then gradually rise in late 2023 to about 1=C2=
=BD percent by the end of the scenario.

Fine, right, recession, real-estate collapse, corporate credit blows out, r=
