10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Stress tests</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a risk manager at a big bank, you m=
ight want to run some stress tests examining how your bank will perform und=
er stressful scenarios. If you are creative and good at your job, you will =
have fun thinking up the scenarios. You will get in a room with some of you=
r subordinates, and ideally with some front-line traders and managers, and =
brainstorm bad stuff that might happen.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Your brainstorming might include some history:=
 =E2=80=9CWhat if 2008 happens again?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhat if 1929 happen=
s again?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhat if <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/31942637.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvTG=
9uZy1UZXJtX0NhcGl0YWxfTWFuYWdlbWVudA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd47db87a" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> LTCM</a> happens again?=E2=80=9D It might include some simple numeric=
al questions: =E2=80=9CWhat if the S&amp;P falls by 20%?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9C=
What if the Fed raises rates to 7%?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhat if the Fed lower=
s rates to 0%?=E2=80=9D You might think about social and geopolitical and t=
echnological questions and try to translate them into economic scenarios: =
=E2=80=9CWhat if nobody goes back to the office and office rents fall 50%?=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhat if artificial intelligence causes mass unemployment=
?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhat if Russia=E2=80=99s war in Ukraine keeps pushing u=
p oil prices?=E2=80=9D You might think about scenarios specific to your ban=
k=E2=80=99s operations: =E2=80=9CWhat if our CEO gets run over by a bus?=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhat if our CEO steals the corporate treasury?=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Have fun, go nuts, be creative. Think of lots =
of scenarios. Then model how those scenarios will translate into market pri=
ces, how they will affect your funding costs and the cash flows from your a=
ssets. Then model how much capital and liquidity you will have in each scen=
ario. Part of the goal here is to make sure that you will have plenty of ca=
pital and liquidity in a wide range of stressful scenarios. Part of the goa=
l is to figure out which scenarios will be worse for you, so you can know w=
hat to worry about and hedge: If your model tells you that you=E2=80=99ll b=
e fine if the Fed raises rates and bankrupt if it lowers rates, maybe you s=
hould do something about that.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If there is some specific event that you are w=
orried about =E2=80=94=C2=A0some new worry that crops up =E2=80=94 you migh=
t sit down and design a stress test for that event to make sure that you=E2=
=80=99d survive it. But your overall approach to stress testing will be som=
ething like =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s constantly think of new things to worry =
about, and test for those.=E2=80=9D It will not be =E2=80=9Clet me think of=
 the one biggest thing to worry about, and test only for that.=E2=80=9D Lot=
s of things can go wrong in different directions! If you only worry about o=
ne thing, you will miss the other things.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also separately the Federal Reserve conducts a=
nnual stress tests for big US banks, but those are =E2=80=A6=C2=A0different=
. The Fed=E2=80=99s stress tests were created after the 2008 crisis, basica=
lly to shore up confidence in the banks so that they could raise capital. T=
he Fed is in the business of supervising big banks, and as part of that bus=
iness it prods the banks to consider various risks, to prepare for differen=
t scenarios, to build a robust culture of stress testing and risk managemen=
t. But the Fed=E2=80=99s official stress tests are a public exercise design=
ed to make sure =E2=80=94=C2=A0and tell everyone =E2=80=94=C2=A0that the ba=
nking system could survive another 2008.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so each year the Fed sits down and thinks =
something like =E2=80=9Cwhat is the most plausible way for 2008 to happen t=
his year,=E2=80=9D and then it writes one stress-test scenario<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> that is basically =E2=80=9Cthere=E2=80=99s a recession and real estate=
 prices collapse,=E2=80=9D and the banks run their models to see how much m=
oney they would lose in that scenario, and generally the answer is =E2=80=
=9Ca certain amount, but not enough to leave us undercapitalized,=E2=80=9D =
and the banks pass the stress tests.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This became <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/31942637.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9u=
ZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjAtMDYtMjkvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtYmFua3MtYXJlLW1hbmFnaW5=
nLXRoZWlyLXN0cmVzcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjI5MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYW=
lsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA2MjkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vb=
mV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB25014147" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> slightly awkward in =
2020</a> when the stress-test scenario involved=C2=A0the US unemployment ra=
te peaking at 10%, while the actual stress of Covid-19 caused unemployment =
to peak at 14.7%. If you ask questions like =E2=80=9Ccan banks survive anot=
her 2008,=E2=80=9D you will not quite get an answer to the question =E2=80=
=9Ccan banks survive a global pandemic?=E2=80=9D The answer to that questio=
n, however, turned out to be yes: For a combination of reasons (supportive =
government policy and Fed lending, but also profiting on volatility), the b=
ig banks did pretty well in Covid.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It also became slightly awkward this year when=
 the Fed released its stress-test scenario=C2=A0in February, and <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31942637.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuZmVkZXJhbHJlc2VydmUuZ292L25ld3NldmVudHMvcHJlc3NyZWxlYXNlcy9maWxlcy9iY3J=
lZzIwMjMwMjA5YTEucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9b405a17" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">it went li=
ke this</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The severely adverse scenario is characterized=
 by a severe global recession accompanied by a period of heightened stress =
in both commercial and residential real estate markets, as well as in corpo=
rate debt markets. The U.S. unemployment rate rises nearly 6=C2=BD percenta=
ge points from the starting point of the scenario in the fourth quarter of =
2022 to its peak of 10 percent in the third quarter of 2024. The sharp decl=
ine in economic activity is also accompanied by an increase in market volat=
ility, widening corporate bond spreads, and a collapse in asset prices, inc=
luding a 38 percent decline in house prices and a 40 percent decline in com=
mercial real estate prices. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rising unemployment rate and the rapid dec=
line in aggregate demand for goods and services significantly reduce inflat=
ionary pressures. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Short-term interest rates, as measured by the =
3-month Treasury rate, fall significantly to near zero by the third quarter=
 of 2023 and remain there for the remainder of the scenario. Long-term inte=
rest rates, as measured by the 10-year Treasury yield, fall by nearly 3=C2=
=BC percentage points by the second quarter of 2023, and then gradually ris=
e in late 2023 to about 1=C2=BD percent by the end of the scenario.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fine, right, recession, real-estate collapse, =
corporate credit blows out, rates go to zero, the 2008 of 2023. But then=C2=
=A0in March a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3194=
2637.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjM=
tMDUtMDEvanBtb3JnYW4tZ290LWEtZGVhbC1vbi1maXJzdC1yZXB1YmxpYz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNj=
I5MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1d=
G1fdGVybT0yMzA2MjkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Bdf583936" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">  couple</a> of US banks <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/31942637.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTAvc3RhcnR1cC1iYW5rLWhhZC1hLXN0YXJ0dXAt=
YmFuay1ydW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyOTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1=
fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNjI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dW=
Zm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd18218b4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  failed</a>, and many others=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31942637.258399/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDQvbm9i=
b2R5LXRydXN0cy10aGUtYmFua3Mtbm93P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjkyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9=
tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDYyOSZ1dG1fY2=
FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB63e8ea90" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  came =
under a lot of stress</a>,=C2=A0for <em>exactly the=C2=A0</em><em>opposite=
=C2=A0</em>reason: Inflation was persistently high, interest rates went up,=
 and those banks had to pay more on deposits even as their holdings of Trea=
sury bonds lost value. Silicon Valley Bank was not subject to the Fed=E2=80=
=99s stress tests, as a mid-sized bank, but if it had been it would have do=
ne great! It did not do great in real life.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway yesterday the 23 big banks subject to t=
he stress tests <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31=
