=E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is intellectually interesting. Broadly speaking the b=
ig banks did a little better in this scenario than in the severe-recession =
scenario.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But also,=C2=A0<em>in real life</em>, the big =
banks did fine in the scenario that actually happened (except Credit Suisse=
!): The problems at US regional banks seem=C2=A0to have driven deposits int=
o the biggest banks, as depositors got nervous about small banks and fled t=
o the safety of big banks. (Look how safe they are, they keep passing the s=
tress tests.) The actual world of 2023 was different from the hypothetical=
=C2=A0world of the stress tests, and in some ways more stressful for the US=
 banking system, but it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
