<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">See <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/31942637.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZGY0ZjM0=
M2MtNTY2Ni00M2EyLWJhMDEtZWYzMTViZmIxMTlh/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfefcf81d"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">this is how banking is supposed to work</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bank of America is bearing the cost of decisio=
ns made three years ago to pump the majority of $670bn in pandemic-era depo=
sit inflows into debt markets at a time when bonds traded at historically h=
igh prices and low yields.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The moves left BofA, the second-largest US ban=
k by assets, with more than $100bn in paper losses at the end of the first =
quarter, according to data from the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation. =
The sum far exceeds unrealised bond market losses reported by its largest p=
eers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The differing results reflect strategies under=
taken early in the Covid-19 pandemic, when banks absorbed a flood of deposi=
ts from savers. BofA put more money into bonds, while others parked a great=
er share in cash.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now that yields have risen and bond prices hav=
e fallen, the value of BofA=E2=80=99s portfolio has plunged. By contrast, J=
PMorgan Chase and Wells Fargo =E2=80=94 the nation=E2=80=99s first and thir=
d-largest banks, respectively =E2=80=94 each had about $40bn in unrealised =
bond market losses, while fourth-largest Citigroup=E2=80=99s paper losses w=
ere $25bn. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BofA has said it has no plans to sell the unde=
rwater bonds, avoiding crystallised losses that for now exist only on paper=
. The bank=E2=80=99s portfolio consists of highly rated government-backed s=
ecurities that are likely to eventually be paid back when the underlying lo=
ans mature.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But holding on to the relatively low-yielding =
investments, many of which are backed by 30-year home loans, at a time when=
 newly purchased bonds yield significantly more, could limit the income tha=
t BofA can generate from its customer deposits.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI think the jury is still out,=E2=80=
=9D said Jason Goldberg, a bank analyst at Barclays, of BofA=E2=80=99s bond=
 portfolio. =E2=80=9CWhen rates were low they were making more money then r=
ivals. Fast-forward to today and they are making less.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The headline on that story is =E2=80=9CBank of=
 America nurses $100bn paper loss after big bet in bond market,=E2=80=9D bu=
t it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=A6=C2=A0kind of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0fine? The key words ar=
e =E2=80=9Cthey are making less.=E2=80=9D When interest rates were near 0%,=
 Bank of America paid about 0.5% on deposits and earned about 2.5% on its p=
ortfolio of long-term Treasury bonds, a spread of about 2=C2=A0percentage p=
oints. Now that interest rates are above 5%, Bank of America pays about 1.4=
% on deposits and earns about 2.6% on its portfolio of long-term Treasury b=
onds, a spread of about 1.2 percentage points.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Obviously you would rather earn 2=C2=A0points than 1.2 points; 2 =
is more than 1.2.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But earning 1.2 points is better than earning,=
 say, nothing, or a negative amount. Bank of America invested a lot of mone=
y in fixed-rate Treasury bonds starting in 2020, and as interest rates went=
 up it has not earned any more money on those Treasuries (because they have=
 fixed rates). But in 2020 it was using cheap deposits to fund those Treasu=
ries, and as interest rates went up it has not had to pay much more money f=
or those deposits. Short-term interest rates have gone up by about 5 percen=
tage points; Bank of America=E2=80=99s deposit rates have gone up by about =
0.9 percentage points; its income from its Treasury portfolio has gone up a=
lmost not at all, so its margins are tighter.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It could be worse! Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31942637.258399/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9ncmFwaGljcy8yMDIzLXVzLWJhbmtzLWV4cGVuc2l2ZS1=
maXgtZGVjbGluaW5nLWRlcG9zaXRzLXByb2JsZW0vP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjkyM19NT05FWVNUVU=
ZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDYyO=
SZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd6cfb910" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">Jennifer Surane, Linly Lin and Mathieu Benhamou report</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">US banks have found a way to replace some of t=
he hundreds of billions of dollars in deposits that flooded out their doors=
 early this year. But it's expensive, and not particularly sticky.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To shore up their books after a flurry of with=
drawals by customers, midsize banks across the US have turned to a patchwor=
k of other sources that demand significantly higher interest, typically aro=
und 5% or more. Regional banks borrowed billions more from the Federal Rese=
rve, Federal Home Loan Bank system and =E2=80=94 to an eye-popping degree =
=E2=80=94 leaned on brokered deposits cobbled together by little-known inte=
rmediaries.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An analysis of quarterly regulatory filings fo=
r the 84 biggest banks =E2=80=94 commanding more than 80% of the industry=
=E2=80=99s assets =E2=80=94 shows not only how much they were borrowing thr=
ough those channels at the end of March, but also the toll that it was just=
 starting to take on some of their earnings. Those rising costs threaten to=
 turn the most strained banks upside down: leaving them paying more to amas=
s the cash they need than they earn by lending it out.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I would not worry=C2=A0<em>so=C2=A0</em>much a=
bout the stickiness there. A bank=E2=80=99s funding from the Fed or the FHL=
Bs is reasonably sticky, in the sense that the Fed and FHLBs seem unlikely =
to pull funding from a bank unless, you know, they=C2=A0<em>want </em>the b=
ank to fail.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the rates are the rates, and they move wit=
h the market.=C2=A0If you are just borrowing money at short-term market rat=
es, well, the rate is about 5%. If you are a US regional bank, you are doin=
g a lot of that. If you are a US regional bank that got a flood of deposits=
 in around 2020 and invested all the money in long-term fixed-rate Treasuri=
es, and then your deposits fled and you had to start borrowing money at sho=
rt-term market rates, well, you are Silicon Valley Bank, or First Republic,=
 and you have disappeared. But if you are a US megabank and you did that, y=
ou=E2=80=99re fine, because your cost of deposits is still pretty low. Bank=
 of America=E2=80=99s realized =E2=80=9Cdeposit beta=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the sensitivity of its deposit rates to the Fed=E2=80=99s interest rates=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0is something like 0.2.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#=
footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: no=
ne !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bl=
ock;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> At some regional banks it was more like 1. If the cost of your funding=
 goes from 0% to 5%, and the yield on your bonds goes from 2.5% to 2.5%, yo=
u go from making 2.5% every year to losing 2.5% every year, and that=E2=80=
=99s bad.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/31942637.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDQvbm9ib2R5LXRydXN0cy10aGUtYmFua3Mtbm93P2NtcGl=
kPUJCRDA2MjkyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbG=
V0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDYyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cC63e8ea90" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked</a> a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/31942637.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNv=
bS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMjIvYmFua3MtZ290LXJpc2luZy1yYXRlcy13cm9=
uZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjI5MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2=
U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA2MjkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cBa0b2913e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  lot</a> about two theories of banki=
ng. The traditional theory is that banks have long-term deposit franchises,=
 and when short-term interest rates rise that has only a minor effect on th=
e banks=E2=80=99 funding costs. Therefore, the banks can and should use the=
ir deposits to buy long-term loans and bonds with long duration, because th=
ey can hold those bonds to maturity. If rates go up, the banks will have ma=
rk-to-market losses on their bonds, but that doesn=E2=80=99t matter: They w=
ill, in some approximate but economically meaningful sense, have=C2=A0<em>o=
ffsetting gains on their deposit franchise</em>. They have cheap long-term =
funding, which allows them to hold long-term bonds to maturity, so the mark=
-to-market losses don=E2=80=99t matter.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other theory is that banks have short-term=
 deposits that can vanish overnight, and that they have to pay short-term m=
arket rates for that deposit funding. If they use that funding to buy long-=
term bonds, and then rates go up, they will earn less on their bonds than t=
hey pay on their deposits, and will have to sell the bonds at a loss, and m=
ight face a bank run and insolvency.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The traditional theory is basically true of th=
e big banks.=C2=A0Bank of America has a $100 billion loss on its bond portf=
olio and doesn=E2=80=99t care. The other theory is basically true of the re=
gional banks.=C2=A0They=E2=80=99re borrowing hot money at 5% and it=E2=80=
=99s a mess.</p>
