 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  The Fifteenth Law of =
Insider Trading</a> is =E2=80=9Cdo not insider trade if you=E2=80=99re a po=
lice chief.=E2=80=9D Just sort of poor form.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The interesting question in cases like this is=
 often: Did the insider (Dupont)=C2=A0<em>intend </em>to tip his buddies so=
 they could trade and make money, or did he just confide in them about work=
 and they betrayed him by trading?<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !=
important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;=
">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0There is no allegation here that Dupont made any=C2=A0<em>money</=
em>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0nobody handed him bags of cash for his tips =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31942=
637.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMy9j=
b21wLXByMjAyMy0xMjIucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB07a4efeb" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> there =
is this</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On April 8, 2020, Dupont participated in a com=
mercial due diligence call with high level leadership from the companies, i=
ncluding both Alexion=E2=80=99s and Portola=E2=80=99s CFO.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The same evening, Cronin and Dupont spoke on t=
he phone for approximately 20 minutes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Later that evening, at 7:49 p.m., Cronin texte=
d Kaplan: =E2=80=9CGood evening, sir. If you need something to take your mi=
nd off of the everyday battle, remember that stock I told you about? Good t=
ime to buy.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not ideal. Also we talk a lot about people who=
 insider trade on merger news by buying short-dated out-of-the-money call o=
ptions, but here=E2=80=99s a new one to me:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On April 23, 2020, at around 3:26 p.m., Feldma=
n texted Kaplan: =E2=80=9CI just bought another PTLA bull spread.=E2=80=9D =
He attached a screenshot of his transaction, such that Kaplan could see Fel=
dman=E2=80=99s options transaction in Portola.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A bull spread or bull call spread is an option=
s transaction that involves buying call options with a lower strike price a=
nd selling call options with the same expiration but a higher strike price.=
 The transaction is profitable when the stock has a limited increase in its=
 price, and is cheaper than purchasing only the lower strike price option.=
=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If a company=E2=80=99s stock is trading at $7,=
 and you know that another company is about to buy it at $18 per share, buy=
ing $10-strike call options is a more efficient way to profit than just buy=
ing the stock at $7: You pay a little bit for the call option, instead of $=
7 for the stock, and still get most of the upside. But buying $10-strike ca=
ll options and selling $18-strike call options is an=C2=A0<em>even more eff=
icient=C2=A0</em>way to profit: You spend even less money up front, and you=
